# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2018-summer-youth-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The **125th IOC Session** took place at the Buenos Aires Hilton in Buenos Aires, Argentina, from 7 to 10 September 2013.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] On 7 September, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) elected Tokyo as the host city of the 2020 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling was restored to the Olympic sports program for 2020 and 2024.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Thomas Bach was elected to an eight-year term as IOC President on 10 September.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The IOC received bids from two cities to host the 125th Session: the Argentine capital Buenos Aires and the Malaysian capital Kuala Lumpur made bids.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Buenos Aires was elected at the 122nd IOC Session in Vancouver which took place prior to the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The members of the IOC elected the host city of the 2020 Olympic Games on 7 September 2013.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The candidates were Tokyo, Istanbul, and Madrid.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Prior to the vote, the contest was considered to be close between the three cities.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Tokyo was awarded the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Following Madrid's elimination after a tie-breaking vote with Istanbul, the three Spanish IOC members were eligible to take part in the final round of voting.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The announcement was met with jubilation from the Tokyo delegation and across Japan.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Abe's role in the final stages of the bid, including his reassurances to the IOC that Fukushima radiation would not affect Tokyo, was considered to be a major asset.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Tokyo's bid had also received support from Princess Hisako and Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad Al-Sabah.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Madrid's bid was considered to have been hampered by Spain's weak economy and Istanbul's was considered to have been damaged by recent internal political instability and doping scandals, as well as match fixing in 2011.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] After Tokyo was selected as host city, the bidding process became the subject of investigations in France concerning payments made by the Tokyo bid committee to Black Tidings, a Singapore-based consultancy.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Reuters reported that Tokyo bid president Tsunekazu Takeda approved a payment of nearly US$1 million to Black Tidings shortly before the 2013 host-city vote, and that Dentsu, an IOC marketing partner, had supported Tokyo's bid campaign.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The Tokyo 2020 organising structure was later affected by separate bribery and bid-rigging investigations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Former Tokyo 2020 executive board member Haruyuki Takahashi, a former senior executive at Dentsu, was accused of receiving payments from companies in connection with Olympic sponsorship and licensing contracts.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] In 2023, Japanese prosecutors indicated Dentsu, Hakuhodo and other companies over alleged bid-rigging related to Tokyo Olympic contracts.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] On 10 September 2013, Thomas Bach of Germany was elected to succeed Jacques Rogge as IOC President, winning in two rounds of voting, over five other candidates.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands was awarded this highest IOC honor on Sunday 8 September after he relinquished his membership to focus on matters at home.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The IOC considered wrestling, squash and baseball/softball to the program for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling had been part of the Ancient Olympic Games and every Modern Olympic Games with the exception of the 1900 Paris Games, however in February 2013 it was dropped from the 2020 Olympic Program.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling successfully campaigned at the 125th Session to be re-included in the 2020 program.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Baseball was first included as a demonstration sport at the 1904 Summer Olympics in St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] It was again played as a demonstration sport at the Summer Olympics in 1912, 1936, 1956, 1964, 1984, and 1988.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] It was first included as an official medal sport at the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Baseball then featured at every Summer Olympic Games until the 2008 Olympics in Beijing, where it made its last Olympic appearance.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Softball was included at the Summer Olympics in 1996, 2000, 2004, and 2008.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The governing bodies for baseball (International Baseball Federation) and softball (International Softball Federation) merged in 2013 to form the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The two sports each had a separate bid for joining the Olympic program.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Although Baseball and Softball were not successful in being included in the 2020 Olympic core program, in 2016 the Tokyo Olympic Organizing Committee and the WBSC successfully campaigned to have the two sports included in the 2020 Games as a one sport, two discipline event for a one-off appearance.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Squash is played in more than 185 countries and by millions of people worldwide.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] It has been played at various international sporting events, including the Pan American Games since 1995, and the All-Africa Games since 2003.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Squash has also been played at both the Commonwealth Games and the Asian Games since 1998.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The sport is governed by the World Squash Federation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling is practiced all around the world, officially in 177 countries, some of which participate in the Olympic Games in this sport alone.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] It was first introduced in the ancient Olympic Games in 708 BC and was included in all the ancient Olympics from that date.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling has featured at the modern Summer Games since the 1896 Olympics in Athens, and it has been a part of all modern Olympics except those in Paris in 1900.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] It was still included in the Olympic program at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] Wrestling was initially dropped from the 2020 Olympic program; however, it was given the opportunity to be reselected for the 2020 and 2024 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/125th-ioc-session] The sport is governed by United World Wrestling.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/127th-ioc-session] The **127th IOC Session** took place in December 2014 in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/127th-ioc-session] All provisions in the Olympic Agenda 2020 reform package were approved by the full IOC membership.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/127th-ioc-session] On December 9, 2014, the IOC members voted for the 131st IOC Session host city in 2017.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/127th-ioc-session] The IOC approved Kosovo's inclusion as a full member of the Committee, allowing the country to participate in Rio 2016 under its national flag and the IOC code of **KOS**.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] The 129th Session of the International Olympic Committee, was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil from August 1 to August 4, 2016, prior to the Games of the XXXI Olympiad, being held in Rio.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] Some key moments of the session included a keynote address from Professor Muhammad Yunus and the election of new sports for the 2020 Olympic program.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] After the introduction of Olympic Agenda 2020 in 2014, the IOC granted Olympic host city organizing committees the ability to propose other sports in addition to the core olympic sports to be included in their respective Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] Several International Sports Federations campaigned to the Tokyo Organizing Committee to be included in the 2020 program; eventually the Tokyo OCOG made the decision to propose the inclusion of baseball/softball(as one sport, two disciplines), karate, skateboarding, sport climbing and surfing.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] The 2020 organizing committee presented the five sport package to the full International Olympic Committee at the IOC session in Rio on August 3, 2016.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/129th-ioc-session] The IOC, unanimously approved the proposal of the inclusion of the five sports for a one-off appearance in the Tokyo Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] The **133rd IOC Session** was an IOC Session held in Buenos Aires, Argentina, on 8 October 2018, during the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] This was the second IOC Session held in Buenos Aires after the 125th IOC Session.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] The Candidature Phase for 2026 Winter Olympics was opened and the host of the 2022 Summer Youth Olympics (Dakar, Senegal) was announced at this IOC Session, the first African host city.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] Before the session the Olympism in Action Forum was held in the city.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] The session took place at the Buenos Aires Hilton in Buenos Aires.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] The Senegal President Macky Sall and Dakar Mayor Soham El Wardini were present at the session.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/133rd-ioc-session] Nine new IOC members were elected at the session.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] They were the first Youth Olympic Games held outside of Eurasia, the first Summer Games held outside of Asia, and the first to be held in the Western and Southern hemispheres.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Six bids were initially submitted for the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Buenos Aires confirmed their bid in September 2011.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] On 13 February 2013, the IOC selected Buenos Aires as one of the three Candidate Cities for the 2018 Summer Youth Olympic Games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The other two candidate cities were Glasgow and Medellín.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Guadalajara and Rotterdam failed to become candidates.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Poznań withdrew their bid before the candidate cities were selected.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The host city election vote was held at an IOC Session in Lausanne.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] In October 2013, International Olympic Committee (IOC) President Thomas Bach appointed Namibian sprinter and four-time Olympic silver medalist Frank Fredericks as Chairman of the Coordination Commission for the 3rd Summer Youth Olympic Games — Buenos Aires 2018.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Fredericks was heading the six-person IOC Coordination Commission made up of several Olympians including Danka Bartekova, the youngest IOC Member and Young Ambassador from the inaugural Youth Olympic Games in Singapore in 2010.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Working along with them there was the Buenos Aires Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (BAYOGOC), that includes member of the Argentine Olympic Committee (AOC), the local government and the national government, and which CEO was Leandro Larrosa.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The first Coordination Commission meeting took place in Buenos Aires on 27–28 September 2014.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The CEOs of Singapore 2010, Lillehammer 2016 and Innsbruck 2012 also took part of these meetings that were presided over by Frank Fredericks.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] In December 2015, the four-time Olympic medalist Luciana Aymar was also named as an ambassador of Buenos Aires 2018.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] In July 2017, Olympic gold medalist Luis Scola was named ambassador of the 2018 YOG.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Joining the Olympic programme for the first time at Buenos Aires 2018 were BMX freestyle, kitesurfing, cross country running, beach handball, sport climbing, karate, breakdancing, and roller sports; and the event programme saw an increased gender balance.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] FIFA also decided to replace football with futsal at the Buenos Aires Youth Olympics, while other sports such as skateboarding were being considered for the programme.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Roller speed skating was added to the Olympic programme on 17 March 2017.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Three years before the event, a survey showed that public support had reached 82.3 per cent in favour of the Youth Olympic games in Buenos Aires.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] During the second visit of the International Olympic Committee's Coordination Commission to the city, on 13 and 14 August 2015, Mr.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Fredericks highlighted the implementation of 13 of the recommendation of the Agenda 2020 by BAYOGOC.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The original plan was based on the bid for the 2004 Summer Olympics, in which a 15 km long *Olympic Corridor* would have worked instead of a more concentrated Olympic Park.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] For the Buenos Aires bid for the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics the *Olympic Corridor* was adapted into a *Green Corridor*, one of the two main sports zones as the primary sites of the Games in Buenos Aires 2018, being the other one Parque Roca, to the south of the city.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The *Green Corridor* and the *Olympic Corridor* shared River Plate Stadium, Tiro Federal, Gimnasia y Esgrima de Buenos Aires, Parque Tres de Febrero, La Bombonera, La Rural and CeNARD as venues.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] In order to group the sports in a more compact framework, in September 2014 a new four-clusters concept was revealed, dropping out venues such as La Rural.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] It was announced then that each cluster would include an area called YOG FEST where sporting experiences, family entertainment and cultural activities would take place.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] But at the 129th IOC Session, in August 2016, a new venues masterplan was presented, including two new stand-alone venues, adding La Rural once again and replacing Parque Sarmiento with Tecnópolis.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The International Olympic Committee members stayed at the Sheraton Hotel, located in the district of Retiro and close to Retiro railway station, one of the most important transportation hubs in Buenos Aires.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] After numerous changes, in February 2018, the definitive venues plan was presented.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Opening Ceremony was held at the Obelisco de Buenos Aires.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Adjacent to downtown Buenos Aires and stretching three kilometres along the scenic banks of the River Plate, this area was distinguished by swathes of parks.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] It included the *barrios* of Núñez and Palermo.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Palermo Woods, a highly popular retreat for *porteños* and visitors alike, was the triathlon and cycling venue.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Venues located in Núñez can be reached by Belgrano Norte Line (at Ciudad Universitaria railway station) or by nearby Mitre Line (at Núñez Station) or Buenos Aires underground Line D (at Congreso de Tucumán Station).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Venues located in Palermo can be reached by Mitre Line (Tres de Febrero and Lisandro de la Torre station).
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Located to the South of Buenos Aires, Roca Park is a vast area of 200 hectares in the district of Villa Soldati, a neighborhood that has been targeted by the local Government in need of urban development.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] One of the greenest areas in the metropolis, it is adjacent to the City Park and the Buenos Aires Automotive Racetrack.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Park, inaugurated in the 1980s, has many sports venues and recreational facilities, including the iconic Roca Park Athletics Stadium and the Roca Park Tennis Stadium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] This area was also the site of the Youth Olympic Village (YOV), from where 65 per cent of the athletes were able to walk to their competition venues, and after the event it would become the new location for the CeNARD.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Parque Polideportivo Roca was fully renovated before the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in order to be used as main Olympic Park.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Six pavilions were built: Asia Pavilion (judo and wrestling), Africa Pavilion (fencing and modern pentathlon), Europe Pavilion (karate and weightlifting), Oceania Pavilion (boxing and taekwondo), America Pavilion (gymnastics) and natatorium.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The complex also includes hockey and athletics fields.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Olympic Park can be reached by Premetro tram at Cecilia Grierson station, or by the southern Metrobus line.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Located to the east of the city, this cluster occupies a significant portion of the Río de la Plata riverbank and includes the old Puerto Madero docks as venue for water sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Rowing competitions were held over 500 metres rather than the usual 2,000 metres.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] This area can be reached by Buenos Aires Underground lines A, B, D and E.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Located west of the city and next to the General Paz Avenue which marks the limit of Buenos Aires city, the 50 hectares science, technology, industry and art mega exhibition Tecnópolis was inaugurated in 2011 and was the venue for four sports competitions.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] This area can be accessed by Mitre Line Railway at Migueletes station or by Belgrano Norte Line at Saavedra or Padilla stations.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics was held at the Obelisco de Buenos Aires on 6 October 2018 at 20:00 (8 PM) Argentina Time.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The 2018 Summer Youth Olympics featured 239 events in 32 sports.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] There were 12 mixed team events (Mixed-NOCs), 9 mixed team events (NOCs), 1 open event (Equestrian), 113 men's events, and 102 women's events.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The schedule for the 2018 Summer Youth Olympic Games was released on 9 May 2018, exactly 150 days before the starting of the games on its official website.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The closing ceremony of the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics was held at the Youth Olympic Village on 18 October 2018.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic flag was handed over to the next host city, Senegalese capital Dakar, for the 2026 Summer Youth Olympics.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Supatchanin Khamhaeng of Thailand originally won the gold medal at the Girls' +63 kg Weightlifting event, but was disqualified in 2019 after testing positive for a banned substance.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The official emblem of the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics was presented in July 2015, three years before the games.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The emblem reflects the diversity of Buenos Aires and it is inspired by the city's vibrant colours, eclectic culture, iconic architecture and the many neighbourhoods that make up the Argentine capital.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] Each letter represents a famous landmark, including the Floralis Genérica, Space Tower, the Columbus Theatre, the National Library and the Obelisk.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] A short video produced by the Buenos Aires Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (BAYOGOC) shows what each letter on the emblem relates to.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The slogan of these Games,"Feel the Future", was unveiled on 8 April 2018.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic mascot of these games was unveiled on 29 May 2018.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The mascot is a young Jaguar, its name "Pandi" is a combination of the scientific name of the species (Panthera onca) and the relationship of the mascot with the "digital world".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The president of the Buenos Aires 2018 Organising Committee, Gerardo Werthein, said that the mascot "seeks to inspire young people on the transformative power of Olympism and sport".
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The mascot was created by the Argentine agency Human Full Agency with direction of Peta Rivero y Hornos.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The animation short was made by the local production company Buda TV.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The official song of Buenos Aires 2018 is "Alive", performed by Candelaria Molfese and Fernando Dente.
[src:2018-summer-youth-olympics/2018-summer-youth-olympics] The name of the song in Spanish is "Vamos juntos" ("Let's go together"), which was also the name of the governing coalition for the 2017 legislative elections in Buenos Aires city.
